04847nam a22006135i 9780822388173DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223881737 a10.1515/97808223881732doi  a(DE-B1597)552611  a(OCoLC)1224277934  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE184.S69bD37 2006 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aDas Gupta, Monisha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnruly Immigrants :bRights, Activism, and Transnational South Asian Politics in the United States /cMonisha Das Gupta. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Encounters -- tChapter 1: Terms of Belonging -- tChapter 2: Contests over Culture -- tChapter 3: Law and Oppression -- tChapter 4: ''Owning Our Lives'': Women's Organizations -- tChapter 5: Subverting Seductions: Queer Organizations -- tChapter 6: ''Know Your Place in History'': Labor Organizations -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Unruly Immigrants, Monisha Das Gupta explores the innovative strategies that South Asian feminist, queer, and labor organizations in the United States have developed to assert claims to rights for immigrants without the privileges or security of citizenship. Since the 1980s many South Asian immigrants have found the India-centered "model minority" politics of previous generations inadequate to the task of redressing problems such as violence against women, homophobia, racism, and poverty. Thus they have devised new models of immigrant advocacy, seeking rights that are mobile rather than rooted in national membership, and advancing their claims as migrants rather than as citizens-to-be. Creating social justice organizations, they have inventively constructed a transnational complex of rights by drawing on local, national, and international laws to seek entitlements for their constituencies.Das Gupta offers an ethnography of seven South Asian organizations in the northeastern United States, looking at their development and politics as well as the conflicts that have emerged within the groups over questions of sexual, class, and political identities. She examines the ways that women's organizations have defined and responded to questions of domestic violence as they relate to women's immigration status; she describes the construction of a transnational South Asian queer identity and culture by people often marginalized by both mainstream South Asian and queer communities in the United States; and she draws attention to the efforts of labor groups who have sought economic justice for taxi drivers and domestic workers by confronting local policies that exploit cheap immigrant labor. Responding to the shortcomings of the state, their communities, and the larger social movements of which they are a part, these groups challenge the assumption that citizenship is the necessary basis of rights claims.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aCitizenshipzUnited States. 0aCivil rights movementszUnited States. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aPolitical activistszUnited States. 0aSocial changezUnited States. 0aSouth Asian AmericansxCivil rights. 0aSouth Asian AmericansxPolitics and government. 0aSouth Asian AmericansxSocieties, etc. 0aTransnationalism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822388173zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://w